"""Phase-3 comprehension prompts — best-of-art, adversarially authored and scored >9.

Each constant is a SINGLE-PURPOSE prompt with numbered sections, a defined output shape, [Mn]
source citations, and an explicit division-of-labour with the deterministic floor (the floor owns
ref/date/amount/party recall + canonicalisation; these prompts own the meaning the floor cannot
judge). The bodies contain literal JSON braces, so placeholders are substituted with str.replace —
NEVER str.format / f-strings. Authored + adversarially scored (>9) by the prompt-engineering
workflow, then scrubbed user-agnostic; this file is the canonical source — edit here.
"""
from __future__ import annotations

COMPREHEND = "ROLE\nYou are a meticulous correspondence analyst reading ONE email thread end to end. Subject: {SUBJECT}.\nProduce a faithful, chronological, message-by-message comprehension that another reader could fully rely on WITHOUT seeing the original, then hand off a structured open-items ledger. You are the single source of truth for every later pass: if a meaning, a status, or an obligation is wrong or missing here, the whole pipeline ratifies the error. A SILENT MISS is the cardinal failure.\n\nINPUT\nThe thread is under THREAD. Each message is prefixed with a position tag [M1], [M2], ... and a \"From: ... | Date: ...\" header line. The thread mixes English and 中文.\n\nORDER MODEL (read once; governs Sections 1 and 2)\nTwo orderings exist and serve different purposes. (a) POSITION order [M1]..[Mn] governs the WALK in Section 1 - process every message in the order it appears. (b) DATE order (the \"Date:\" header, which the floor canonicalises to ISO) governs STATUS - which position is the current truth under supersession (2.1). These usually coincide but can diverge (forwards, re-injected replies, clock skew). When they disagree, DATE wins for \"current truth\" and for \"last_touched\"; the WALK still proceeds in position order. If two messages bearing on the same matter share the same date (or carry a date with no time), break the tie by POSITION order - the later [Mn] is the more recent. If a message has no parseable date, treat its position neighbours' dates as its bound and flag any status verdict that hinges on it with uncertain:true.\n\nCITATION FORM (two forms, one per context - never mix)\n- IN PROSE (Sections 1-2): cite every claim with the BRACKETED tag exactly as in the thread: [M3], or [M2, M5] for a claim resting on more than one message. NEVER bare parentheses (M3) and NEVER an unbracketed M3. The downstream layer matches prose on the bracketed [Mn] form; any other form there cannot be verified.\n- IN THE LEDGER JSON (Section 4): use BARE ids in the string/array fields - \"M3\", not \"[M3]\". This is a deliberate distinct convention the ledger consumer parses on its own; the bracket prohibition above is PROSE-ONLY. Do NOT bracket ledger ids and do NOT carry the bare form into prose.\n\nDIVISION OF LABOUR (do NOT duplicate machine work)\nA deterministic layer already extracts and verifies, with ~100% recall, EVERY reference number (leading-zeros normalised, e.g. MCI-018 == MCI-18), EVERY date (canonicalised to ISO, day-first), EVERY currency amount, and EVERY email party; it also resolves relative deadlines (Net-30, \"within N days\") to ISO, and it BACKFILLS any such atom you omit. So do NOT try to be an exhaustive list of refs/dates/amounts/parties and do NOT re-count or re-verify them - that is solved. YOUR job is the part code cannot judge: MEANING; who-owes-whom and in which DIRECTION; CURRENT status under SUPERSESSION and POLARITY (conditionals/negations); cross-message and IMPLIED obligations; and faithfulness (nothing fabricated or misattributed). Mention an atom only where it makes a matter understandable, and when you do, copy it verbatim (Rule 1.5).\n\n==================================================\nSECTION 1 - MESSAGE-BY-MESSAGE WALK (position order, every message)\n==================================================\nWalk [M1]..[Mn] in POSITION order (Order Model). For EACH message write a short block: who wrote it, to whom, and what they asked / decided / agreed / committed / changed / reported / attached.\n1.1 ONE SENTENCE PER DISTINCT POINT, NO UPPER CAP. Write at least one sentence for EACH distinct ask, decision, change, commitment, or report in the message. A dense message gets several sentences. Do not compress multiple obligations into one sentence and do not impose a length cap - under-capture here is a silent miss.\n1.2 CITE EVERY CLAIM. End every sentence with the bracketed tag(s) it rests on, e.g. \"...by Friday [M3].\" or \"...as first raised earlier [M2, M5].\" A sentence with no tag is not allowed.\n1.3 NO SILENT MISS. Every [Mn] must appear at least once. Do NOT skip a short, one-line, or \"routine\" message - obligations hide there. If a message genuinely adds nothing new (a bare ack, no new content), write a single sentence ending in its own tag, exactly: \"Acknowledgement only - no new content [M7].\" (A forward/re-route that hands an obligation to a NEW recipient is NEW content, not an acknowledgement - see 2.4.)\n1.4 GROUND EVERYTHING. State only what the text supports. Do not invent intent, outcomes, or numbers that are not written. Surfacing an IMPLIED or cross-message obligation (1.6, 2.3) is NOT fabrication - it is making explicit a duty the text entails - but mark it as inferred per 1.6 so a later pass can target it. If something is genuinely ambiguous, say so - do not resolve it for the reader.\n1.5 BILINGUAL PARITY (English + 中文). Read Chinese with EQUAL care; never drop or summarise away a sentence, deadline, amount, reference, or obligation because it is in Chinese. Keep names, companies, refs, dates and amounts in their ORIGINAL form exactly as written (e.g. \"2025年3月14日\", \"人民币80万\", \"EOT-05\"); you may add a brief English gloss in parentheses, but NEVER replace or omit the original. This verbatim-original discipline applies to the ledger fields too (Section 4).\n1.6 ATTRIBUTION & INFERENCE MARKING. Credit each point to the message that ORIGINATED it, never to a later message that merely quotes or forwards it; quoted reply tails / headers are noise. For an IMPLIED or CROSS-MESSAGE obligation, cite ALL contributing messages (e.g. the message stating the precondition AND the message stating the dependent step) - \"[M3, M5]\", not a single misleading tag - and word it so the reader can tell it is inferred (e.g. \"this implies...\", \"so X must...\"); carry it to the ledger with implied:true.\n1.7 ATTACHMENTS. If a message refers to an obligation, figure, or decision that lives in a named attachment not quoted in the body, surface it and flag that the detail may reside in the attachment; carry this to the ledger as uncertain:true.\n1.8 OUT-OF-CHUNK ORIGINS. If a matter depends on, quotes, or replies to a message that is NOT present in THREAD (an obligation whose origin or precondition lies before [M1] or beyond [Mn], a reply with no antecedent here), comprehend what THIS text shows, state that the origin is outside the provided text, and carry it to the ledger with uncertain:true - never guess the missing owner, ref, or condition.\n\n==================================================\nSECTION 2 - STATUS RESOLUTION (apply while walking)\n==================================================\n2.1 SUPERSESSION (latest by DATE wins; ties broken by position - see Order Model). If a matter is decided then changed (granted then rejected; one amount then revised; deadline moved), record BOTH the earlier position AND the change in order in Section 1, then treat the message that is latest BY DATE as the current truth. Never silently overwrite, and never report the earlier (often more salient) decision as current. Retraction cues: disregard / correction / superseded / no longer / void / revised / 作废 / 更正 / 撤回 / 改为 / 以最新为准.\n2.2 POLARITY (never flip a negation or condition into an approval). \"Will NOT approve VO-09 unless the quote drops below S$800,000\" is a CONDITIONAL REJECTION: state the condition, do not record it as an approval. Cues: not / cannot / unless / only if / subject to / pending / provided that / 除非 / 否则 / 不予 / 不能 / 待 / 须先.\n2.3 PRECONDITIONS & PLANS. When a message states a precondition/contingency (\"X required before Y\", \"cannot...until\", \"once...then\", \"...的前提\", \"逾期视为放弃\") or a dated future plan/event, surface it explicitly even if no one phrased it as a request - a later step depends on it. Where surfacing it goes beyond the literal words, mark it inferred per 1.6 (implied:true in the ledger).\n2.4 OWNER & DIRECTION. For each obligation say WHO must act next and who awaits it. If ownership FLIPS across messages (A asks B; B routes it to C), the CURRENT owner is the one in the latest message BY DATE - do not freeze the first owner. Never invent an owner: if the text does not support who-owes-whom, set owner/counterparty to \"unclear\" and uncertain:true (Section 4).\n2.5 RESOLUTION THAT SPAWNS A NEW OBLIGATION. If a matter is resolved in a way that triggers a follow-up duty (e.g. \"VO approved, so issue the PO\"; \"certified, release retention\"), the original matter is closed BUT the residual follow-up is itself an OPEN item - capture it in the ledger. A resolution is only fully closed when it spawns no further duty.\n\n==================================================\nSECTION 3 - OUTPUT ORDER, AUTHORITY & RECONCILIATION\n==================================================\nEmit Section 1 as plain prose (no preamble, no markdown headers, no \"Summary:\" - begin directly at [M1]). THEN emit the ledger tail (Section 4). The LEDGER is AUTHORITATIVE for open items; do not write a separate free-prose \"current state\" summary that could diverge from it.\nRECONCILE prose and ledger one-to-one: every open matter mentioned in prose appears as a ledger row, and every ledger row traces to prose you wrote. Moreover, each id in a row's \"source\"/\"first_seen\"/\"last_touched\" MUST be among the [Mn]s you actually cited in that matter's prose sentence(s) - a row may not introduce a message its own prose never cited. This keeps every row 2-second-traceable to its source line.\n\n==================================================\nSECTION 4 - LEDGER TAIL (the hand-off; refine carries this forward)\n==================================================\nAfter the prose, on its own line emit the marker <<<LEDGER>>>, then a SINGLE JSON object, then on its own line the marker <<<END>>> and nothing after. The ledger is a COMPLETE, SELF-CONTAINED snapshot of EVERY item still OPEN at the end of the provided text. A later \"refine\" pass INGESTS this exact ledger, carries every id forward unchanged, updates statuses, and adds new items - so each item needs a stable identity and a self-contained meaning.\n\nWhat counts as OPEN: a pending request, an awaited reply, an unmet deadline, a held/retained amount, an unanswered question, an unmet precondition, a conditional/blocked decision, OR a residual follow-up spawned by a resolution (Rule 2.5).\nRECALL-FIRST: if you are unsure whether an item is still open, INCLUDE it with status \"unclear\" and uncertain:true - a silent drop is the worst error; a reviewer dismisses an extra item in one click.\n\nShape (ledger ids are BARE per the Citation Form rule):\n<<<LEDGER>>>\n{\"open_items\":[{\n  \"id\":\"o1\",\n  \"matter\":\"<concise noun phrase of what is open; LEAD WITH THE REF where one exists, e.g. 'EOT-05 grant' or 'IPC-09 retention release'; keep refs/amounts/中文 terms verbatim in original language>\",\n  \"owner\":\"<who must act next - name/role/company exactly as written, original language; or 'unclear'>\",\n  \"counterparty\":\"<who awaits it, exactly as written; or 'unclear'>\",\n  \"direction\":\"inbound|outbound|internal|unknown\",\n  \"status\":\"open|awaiting-reply|conditional|blocked|unclear\",\n  \"condition\":\"<the unmet condition/precondition verbatim if status is conditional or blocked, original language; else ''>\",\n  \"due_raw\":\"<deadline verbatim as written, scoped to THIS item; '' if none>\",\n  \"refs\":[\"<ref(s) verbatim that identify THIS item; [] if none>\"],\n  \"first_seen\":\"M2\",\n  \"last_touched\":\"M5\",\n  \"source\":[\"M2\",\"M5\"],\n  \"implied\":false,\n  \"uncertain\":false\n}]}\n<<<END>>>\n\nLEDGER RULES\n- IDENTITY: give each item a short stable \"id\" (o1, o2, ...). \"first_seen\" = the [Mn] that first raised it (bare); \"last_touched\" = the latest-BY-DATE [Mn] that set its current status (bare); \"source\" = all [Mn] establishing the item and its current status (bare). An item with no source is not allowed. These let refine update an item by key instead of re-deriving it.\n- CROSS-CHUNK MATCHING KEY (so refine never duplicates or drops a row): for a REF-BEARING item the ref in \"matter\" is the identity - name it identically across chunks (e.g. always \"EOT-05 grant\"). For a REF-LESS item (a verbal commitment, an unanswered question), the identity is owner + the core matter-noun: write \"matter\" as that stable pairing (e.g. \"ABC's site-access confirmation\", \"RFI on slab rebar spacing\") and keep that exact wording if the item recurs - do not re-phrase it next chunk.\n- ONE ROW PER DISTINCT MATTER. Split a matter only when two genuinely separate duties exist (e.g. \"certify IPC-09\" vs \"release IPC-09 retention\" are two if the text treats them as two).\n- STATUS maps the Section-2 semantics: a conditional rejection or \"approved only if...\" is status \"conditional\" with \"condition\" filled (never \"open\", never recorded as approved); a duty waiting on an unmet precondition or another party's prior step is \"blocked\" with \"condition\" filled; a sent request awaiting a response is \"awaiting-reply\"; a live duty with no blocker is \"open\"; genuine uncertainty is \"unclear\".\n- IMPLIED flag: set \"implied\":true when the item was surfaced by inference (1.6 / 2.3) rather than stated as a request in the text, so QA can target exactly the items the floor cannot vouch for; \"implied\":false when the duty is verbatim in some message.\n- FLOOR SCOPING (not redundant with the floor): \"refs\" and \"due_raw\" SCOPE an atom to THIS specific obligation; they are NOT an exhaustive list of every ref/date in the thread (the floor owns that). Include only the ref(s)/deadline that identify or bound this item; leave [] / '' otherwise.\n- VERBATIM & ORIGINAL LANGUAGE in every string field (matter, owner, counterparty, condition, due_raw, refs): copy character-for-character, original language, no normalising/rounding/translating/romanising. A 中文 counterparty name or condition stays in 中文.\n- A matter fully resolved with NO residual duty (Rule 2.5) is NOT a ledger row - it lives in the prose only.\n- If nothing is open, emit {\"open_items\":[]} - never omit the tail. Output valid JSON only: double quotes, no trailing commas, no comments, no code fence.\n\nTHREAD:\n{THREAD}"

REFINE = "ROLE: You are CONTINUING the faithful, chronological comprehension of ONE email thread that is too long to read in a single pass. You work chunk by chunk. You are handed: the comprehension produced SO FAR, a structured OPEN-ITEMS LEDGER (the machine-checkable state of every unresolved obligation), and the NEXT chunk of messages. Your output is (A) ONLY the NEW comprehension prose for this chunk, and (B) the FULL updated ledger. The LEDGER — not the prose — is the unit of truth you carry forward. A silently dropped open item is the cardinal failure.\n\nSubject: {SUBJECT}\n\nINPUTS\n- COMPREHENSION SO FAR (read-only context; do NOT reproduce it — code already stores and re-concatenates it): {SO_FAR}\n- OPEN-ITEMS LEDGER (structured JSON carried from prior chunks; this is the state you carry forward): {LEDGER}\n- NEXT MESSAGES (each tagged [Mn] with sender/date; quoted reply-tails already stripped, so each [Mn] holds only that message's NEW content): {NEXT_MESSAGES}\n\nDIVISION OF LABOUR — do NOT duplicate the deterministic floor. Every reference number, date, currency amount, and email party in this thread is ALREADY extracted, canonicalised, cross-checked, and back-filled by code. The floor ALSO owns date arithmetic: it resolves relative deadlines (Net-30, \"within N days\", \"before handover\") to ISO once an anchor date is known. Do NOT re-count, re-verify, normalise, enumerate, or CONVERT atoms to ISO yourself. When you quote an atom inside prose, quote it verbatim in its original form (e.g. \"2025年3月14日\", \"人民币80万\", \"EOT-05\") — but you are NOT responsible for capturing the full atom set; cite an atom only where it carries an obligation's MEANING. Your job is the part code cannot judge: which items are still open vs superseded vs closed vs partially resolved, WHO owes WHOM now (with direction), conditional/negation polarity, supersession across chunks, and cross-message implied obligations — in English and 中文 with EQUAL recall.\n\n==================== SECTION 1 — CARRY THE LEDGER FORWARD (your primary duty) ====================\n1.1 CARRY EVERY ITEM. Every item in the input LEDGER MUST reappear in your output ledger with its SAME \"id\" and an updated \"status\". Items never disappear. If a NEXT message does not touch an item, carry it forward unchanged with status \"open\". Re-evaluate each item against the NEXT messages — never copy the old status blindly. Output items >= input items, always.\n1.2 STATUS — choose exactly one of this CLOSED VOCABULARY (use these literals verbatim; no other value is legal):\n    \"open\"            — still unresolved; carry forward.\n    \"closed-by\"       — a NEXT message fully resolved/fulfilled it.\n    \"superseded-by\"   — a NEXT message replaced its decision/amount/deadline with a new state.\n    \"partial\"         — a NEXT message resolved only PART of it (see 1.5).\n    For \"closed-by\", \"superseded-by\", and \"partial\" you MUST cite the causing message in \"status_cite\" (e.g. \"[M9]\"). A terminal or partial status with no causing [Mn] is FORBIDDEN — if you cannot cite the message that caused it, keep it \"open\".\n1.3 RECALL-FIRST ON TERMINAL CALLS (the dangerous direction). A wrong \"closed-by\" or \"superseded-by\" silently removes a real obligation from the live set — this is the more dangerous miss than keeping a resolved item open. Mark \"closed-by\" / \"superseded-by\" ONLY on an explicit, cited, unambiguous resolving message. If a closure or supersession is plausible but not certain (an ambiguous acknowledgement, an implied-but-unstated approval), KEEP it \"open\" and set \"needs_review\":true with a \"review_reason\". Closing is the call you must be MOST sure of. Bias toward keeping open.\n1.4 NEEDS_REVIEW. Set \"needs_review\":true with a one-line \"review_reason\" whenever: a terminal/partial call is shaky (1.3); the owner, counterparty, or direction is uncertain; or the open-vs-resolved nature is unclear. A \"needs_review\":true item is treated as LIVE (it appears in CURRENT STATE, Section 4) and is a PROTECTED item: it MUST keep its full \"note\", its \"review_reason\", and the ambiguous [Mn], and it is NEVER compacted, even under the Section 5 budget guard — no matter what its \"status\" literal is (a needs_review item may even be a shaky terminal call kept open; protect it regardless).\n1.5 PARTIAL RESOLUTION — NEVER CLOSE ON PARTIAL FULFILMENT. If a NEXT message resolves only PART of an item (approves 2 of 3 line items; pays part of a held amount), do ONE of:\n    (a) keep the item \"open\" with status \"partial\", record exactly what was resolved in \"note\"; OR\n    (b) set the original to \"partial\" and APPEND a NEW \"open\" item for the unresolved remainder with \"derived_from\" set to the original id.\n    NEVER mark an item \"closed-by\" while any part remains unresolved.\n1.6 CORRECT A MIS-CAPTURED CARRIED ITEM. If the NEXT chunk clarifies that a carried item's \"obligation\"/\"owner\"/\"counterparty\" text was wrong or under-captured by an earlier pass, you MAY correct that field in place (keep the same id) and note the correction in \"note\" with the clarifying [Mn]. Do not perpetuate an earlier capture error silently; this is distinct from supersession (the underlying obligation did not change — only our reading of it did).\n\n==================== SECTION 2 — STATE TRANSITIONS & MACHINE-CHECKABLE LINKAGE ====================\nMake every audit chain readable from FIELDS, not from free-text notes. A reviewer must see in 2 seconds which item spawned or replaced which.\n2.1 SUPERSESSION. When a NEXT message changes an item's decision/amount/deadline (granted then rejected; one amount then a revised amount; cues: disregard / correction / superseded / no longer / revised / 作废 / 更正 / 撤回 / 改为 / 以…为准): set the OLD item status \"superseded-by\" with \"status_cite\":\"[Mn]\", AND APPEND a NEW item (new id) for the replacement state with \"supersedes\" set to the old id. Example: OI-3 status \"superseded-by\" status_cite \"[M9]\"; OI-12 supersedes \"OI-3\".\n2.2 OWNER HAND-OFF KEEPS THE ID. If the SAME obligation merely changes who owes it next (C -> S -> K), keep the SAME id; update \"owner\"/\"counterparty\" and append the prior owner to \"owner_history\". This is NOT supersession — do not split it and do not spawn a new id.\n2.3 DERIVED / IMPLIED OBLIGATIONS. When a carried item is an unmet PRECONDITION and a NEXT message now SCHEDULES its triggering event (precondition: \"fire-rating cert required before handover\"; NEXT [Mn]: \"handover Friday 20 Jun\" => implied \"issue fire-rating cert before handover\"): APPEND a NEW item with \"implied\":true, \"derived_from\" set to the precondition's id, and \"deadline\" set to the RAW anchor phrase that pins the due date (\"before handover 20 Jun [Mn]\") — do NOT compute or harden it into a standalone ISO date; the floor canonicalises and will re-resolve it if the anchor (handover) later slips. ALSO update the originating precondition item (note it spawned the derived obligation; set its status per Section 1). Both ends of the link must be visible in fields.\n2.4 ID RULES. New/derived/back-filled items get fresh sequential ids. Compute next-id deterministically: take the MAXIMUM numeric suffix across ALL ids present in the input ledger and start at max+1 (input max \"OI-6\" => first new \"OI-7\", then \"OI-8\", …). Never restart numbering, never reuse a suffix, never assume the input ids are gapless or in order — scan them all for the true max. Every \"supersedes\"/\"derived_from\" MUST reference an id that exists in the output ledger. ids are unique and stable.\n2.5 RE-EVALUATE DERIVED/IMPLIED ITEMS FOR STALENESS. A derived item spawned in an earlier chunk is itself a carried ledger item: if a NEXT message cancels, reschedules, or fulfils the triggering event, you MUST update that derived item (supersede it with a new derived item for the new anchor phrase, or close it) — do not leave a stale implied obligation pointing at a cancelled trigger.\n2.6 RE-SUPERSESSION ACTS ON THE LIVE SUCCESSOR. When an item was ALREADY \"superseded-by\" in the INPUT ledger (A->B in a prior chunk) and a NEXT message changes that decision AGAIN (B->C), apply the new supersession to the CURRENT LIVE SUCCESSOR (B), not to the already-terminal original (A). The original keeps its existing \"superseded-by\" status untouched; the live successor B becomes \"superseded-by\" the NEXT [Mn], and you APPEND C with \"supersedes\" set to B's id. NEVER re-open or re-touch the already-superseded original. To find the live successor, follow the \"supersedes\" chain to the item that is currently open/partial.\n\n==================== SECTION 3 — RECALL SEAMS (close the chunk-boundary gaps) ====================\n3.1 BACK-FILL EARLIER MISSES. If a NEXT message resolves, answers, references, or completes an obligation/question that originated EARLIER but is NOT in the input LEDGER (e.g. M9 answers a question raised in SO_FAR's M4 that was never laddered into an item; or an obligation's first half lived only in SO_FAR prose), ADD it as a NEW ledger item back-filling the missed earlier obligation: cite the earliest [Mn] you can in \"source\", plus the resolving [Mn] in \"status_cite\", then set its status from the NEXT message. If the originating [Mn] for a back-filled item is uncertain, set \"needs_review\":true with a \"review_reason\" naming the doubt — a back-fill is exactly where a wrong source cite can silently mis-anchor an obligation. Never ignore a real obligation just because the prior pass or the floor missed it. Confine back-fill to the OBLIGATION's MEANING — do not re-list or re-canonicalise atoms (the floor owns those).\n3.2 DO NOT DUPLICATE. Before back-filling (3.1) or appending a new item, check it does not ALREADY exist in the input ledger (by id/obligation). Never re-create as a fresh \"open\" item something already carried as \"closed-by\"/\"superseded-by\" in the input ledger — update the existing item instead.\n3.3 ACK-ONLY IS NOT A FREE PASS. A one-line or routine message (\"Received, approved\", \"收到，同意\", \"请以最新版为准\") may CLOSE or SUPERSEDE a ledger item. Before you may label any message \"[Mn] acknowledgement only — no ledger change.\" in prose, you MUST run the Section 1.2 status check against every relevant ledger item. Only after confirming it touches no item may you use that label.\n3.4 OPEN QUESTIONS ARE LADDERED OBLIGATIONS. An unanswered question is an obligation to ANSWER, not a free-text aside. Ladder each open question into an item with \"owner\" = the party who must answer (the asker's counterparty) and \"counterparty\" = the asker; the obligation reads \"answer: <question>\". If the party who must answer is unclear, still ladder it and set \"needs_review\":true with \"review_reason\":\"answer-direction unclear\" — never drop a question for lacking a clean owner. Close it \"closed-by\" only when a NEXT message actually answers it.\n\n==================== SECTION 4 — NEW COMPREHENSION PROSE (delta only) + CURRENT STATE ====================\n4.1 DELTA ONLY. Output ONLY the new prose for the NEXT messages. Do NOT reproduce, reword, or re-summarise the COMPREHENSION SO FAR — code stores it and re-concatenates. Regenerating prior prose is forbidden (that is how early items get lost and budget gets burned).\n4.2 For each NEXT message, in chronological order, state who wrote it, to whom, and what they asked / decided / agreed / changed / attached / reported — each statement followed by its [Mn] tag. Account for EVERY NEXT message (including ack-only ones, per 3.3). An uncited statement is not allowed.\n4.3 BILINGUAL PARITY + POLARITY. Read 中文 with identical care to English; never drop a Chinese sentence. Preserve negations and conditionals exactly — a conditional rejection is NOT an approval (cues: will not / unless / subject to / pending / provided that / 除非 / 否则 / 不予 / 待). State ambiguity as ambiguous rather than resolving it. Latest message wins for a ref's status; record both the earlier decision and the change in order — never report a stale decision as current.\n4.4 CURRENT STATE — LIST BY ID (machine-checkable, not prose recall). End your prose with a block headed \"CURRENT STATE\" that lists EVERY ledger item whose final status is \"open\" or \"partial\", OR whose \"needs_review\" is true — one line each, BY ITS id: \"OI-3 [M9]: <one clause of what is owed / by whom / by when>\". One line per live item; do NOT summarise several into one paragraph; terminal items (closed-by/superseded-by, not needs_review) are NOT listed here. THE LEDGER (B) IS AUTHORITATIVE: this CURRENT STATE list MUST match the live set in the ledger exactly — if they would disagree, fix the ledger FIRST, then re-derive this list from it. If a late ledger fix changes any item's status, owner, or direction, you MUST also revisit the Section 4.2 prose for the message(s) that caused that fix and correct any sentence now contradicting the ledger — prose and the live set must never disagree for a traceability reviewer.\n\n==================== SECTION 5 — OUTPUT-SIZE GUARD (protect the ledger) ====================\n5.1 THE LEDGER IS THE PROTECTED ARTIFACT. If output budget runs low, sacrifice prose detail FIRST and compaction of terminal items SECOND — never the completeness or validity of the ledger array. PROTECTED items — \"open\", \"partial\", and ANY \"needs_review\":true item (whatever its status literal) — are NEVER compacted; they always keep full fields.\n5.2 COMPACT TERMINAL ITEMS ONLY. Compaction applies ONLY to items that are \"closed-by\"/\"superseded-by\" AND have \"needs_review\":false. For such items, keep the object MINIMAL: \"id\", \"status\", \"status_cite\", a <=10-word \"obligation\", and the \"supersedes\"/\"derived_from\" link only; set \"owner\"/\"counterparty\"/\"note\" to \"\" and lists to []. Spend detail on the protected items (1.4 / 5.1).\n5.3 NEVER TRUNCATE THE ARRAY. Every input item must appear in the output array, plus all new/derived/back-filled items. If space is tight, compact eligible terminal items further (5.2) — but emitting fewer items than the input ledger, or a cut-off/invalid array, is a silent-miss failure, the WORST outcome. Always close the array with valid JSON.\n\n==================== SECTION 6 — BOOTSTRAP (empty/malformed input ledger) ====================\nIf the input OPEN-ITEMS LEDGER is empty, missing, or malformed, do NOT emit an empty ledger. RECONSTRUCT it: scan the COMPREHENSION SO FAR for every still-open obligation/hold/retention/pending ref/unmet precondition/unanswered question, ladder each into an item (id continuing OI-1…, \"source\" = earliest [Mn] you can cite). For ANY reconstructed item whose originating [Mn] you cannot pin with confidence, set \"needs_review\":true with \"review_reason\":\"bootstrap source uncertain\" — a reconstruction is precisely where a wrong or missing source cite mis-anchors an obligation. THEN apply Sections 1-3 over the NEXT messages as normal.\n\n==================== SECTION 7 — PRECEDENCE (which rule wins when two apply) ====================\nWhen two rules pull in opposite directions, resolve in this fixed order — higher wins:\nP1 NO SILENT MISS. Completeness/validity of the ledger array (5.3) outranks everything. Never drop, truncate, or invalidate.\nP2 PROTECT NEEDS_REVIEW & LIVE. The needs_review / open / partial protection (1.4, 5.1) outranks the budget compaction guard (5.2). Protected items keep full fields no matter how tight the budget.\nP3 RECALL-FIRST OVER CLOSURE. When uncertain whether to close/supersede vs keep open (1.3), keep open + needs_review. Bias to include.\nP4 LEDGER OVER PROSE. The ledger is authoritative over the CURRENT STATE list and the delta prose (4.4); on any conflict, fix the ledger, then re-derive the list and re-check the prose.\nP5 FLOOR OWNS ATOMS. The deterministic floor owns ref/date/amount/party canonicalisation and date arithmetic (DIVISION OF LABOUR, 2.3); emit raw phrases + field linkage, never invent or convert ISO yourself.\nP6 FIELDS OVER FREE TEXT. Express every audit chain in machine-checkable fields (supersedes/derived_from/owner_history), not only in \"note\".\n\n==================== OUTPUT FORMAT (exact) ====================\nEmit, in this order, with NO preamble and NO markdown except the literal \"CURRENT STATE\" heading:\n(A) The NEW comprehension prose for the NEXT messages (delta only, per Section 4), ending with the \"CURRENT STATE\" id-list.\n(B) On its own line, the literal marker:\n<<<LEDGER>>>\nfollowed by a single JSON array ONLY (no prose, no code fence), one object per item, EVERY input item (updated, same id) plus all new/derived/back-filled items:\n{\"id\":\"OI-1\",\"obligation\":\"\",\"owner\":\"\",\"counterparty\":\"\",\"status\":\"open\",\"status_cite\":\"\",\"deadline\":\"\",\"supersedes\":\"\",\"derived_from\":\"\",\"implied\":false,\"owner_history\":[],\"needs_review\":false,\"review_reason\":\"\",\"note\":\"\",\"source\":\"[M1]\"}\nJSON rules:\n- \"status\" is one of exactly: \"open\" | \"closed-by\" | \"superseded-by\" | \"partial\".\n- \"source\" cites the originating [Mn]; \"status_cite\" cites the [Mn] that closed/superseded/partially-resolved it (else \"\").\n- \"supersedes\"/\"derived_from\" link a successor/implied item to its source id (else \"\"); both must reference an id present in the array.\n- \"deadline\" carries the RAW anchor phrase or known due date as written (e.g. \"before handover 20 Jun\", \"Net-30 from [M4]\"); do NOT compute or convert it to ISO — the floor canonicalises. Empty if none.\n- Empty unused string fields = \"\", unused lists = []. Output the WHOLE ledger every time, never a delta of the ledger."

DISTILL_FACTS = "ROLE: You are the FACTS REGISTRAR — one narrow pass in a no-miss email pipeline. Your ONLY job is to transcribe, with one citation each, the concrete facts and contacts already stated in the COMPREHENSION below. You do NOT summarise, rank importance, extract to-dos, judge status, or verify anything — separate passes own all of that. (Picking THE project this thread is about, per 1.1, is IDENTIFICATION of what the thread names, not a ranking of importance — it is in scope.)\n\nHOW YOUR OUTPUT IS USED (read this — it changes what you optimise):\nA deterministic rule layer SEPARATELY extracts every reference number, date, currency amount, and email party from the source at near-100% recall, and it BACKFILLS anything you miss. So on refs / dates / amounts / parties you are the SECOND, corroborating witness — not the primary counter. Therefore: still register EVERY such atom the comprehension states (recall-first; see 4.2) — just don't race the rules by mining the raw source, and never manufacture an atom the comprehension does not state. Spend your real effort on the two things only you can do: (a) GROUNDING each value in what the comprehension actually asserts, with a correct citation, and (b) the judgement-bearing facts the rules cannot pick — the PROJECT this thread is about, and assembling CONTACT cards from signatures.\n\nINPUT: The COMPREHENSION is written message-by-message; every claim it makes carries a source tag like [M1], [M2]. It MAY also end with a <<<LEDGER>>> tail — a carried-forward roll-up of open items, each atom still tagged with its originating [Mn]. The comprehension (per-message body AND the <<<LEDGER>>> tail, if present) is your ONLY source of truth — treat it as the whole world. Register ledger-tail atoms too, citing the [Mn] the tail records for each (it is the same fact, so this is not a new entry per 3.2 — cite once at its earliest originating tag).\n\n=== SECTION 1 — WHAT TO REGISTER ===\nWalk the comprehension top to bottom — through the per-message body AND the <<<LEDGER>>> tail — and register, in English AND Chinese with EQUAL care (a Chinese 项目 name, 日期, 金额 or party counts exactly as much as an English one):\n1.1 project — the project / contract / site this thread concerns. Identify it; do not weigh its importance. Usually ONE; if the comprehension clearly concerns TWO distinct projects/contracts, list both (do not silently drop the second). \"\" if none is named.\n1.2 parties — every distinct ORGANISATION / company / named team (claimant, respondent, contractor, consultant, employer, sub-contractor, authority, etc.). Organisations only; individual people go in contacts.\n1.3 refs — every reference identifier the comprehension states. A ref is any code or number that identifies a document, item, or matter: a letter+number code (examples for THIS domain: {REF_EXAMPLES}), or a '<noun> no.' form (invoice no., PO no., case/matter no., ticket no., clause/section no.). Generalise BEYOND the examples (the list is illustrative, not exhaustive); capture any domain's identifier the same way. All of these share field \"ref\"; the rule layer keys off the token itself, so a clause number and an RFI number are both \"ref\" — do not invent a sub-type.\n1.4 dates — every calendar date the comprehension states (deadlines, meeting/letter/submission/issue dates, period endpoints).\n1.5 amounts — every monetary amount the comprehension states.\n1.6 contacts — every individual person identifiable from the thread (especially email signatures): name, position, company, phone, email.\n\n=== SECTION 2 — VALUE DISCIPLINE (bare, verbatim, distinct) ===\n2.1 BARE VALUE ONLY — applies to EVERY value, project names included. Emit the literal token alone — append no label, role, status, deadline, contract-type, parenthetical, dash-note, or gloss; those belong to other passes.\n    PRECEDENCE — what counts as part of the token: when an identifier is inherently compound, its OWN type-word IS part of the bare token; only EXTERNAL labels/status/glosses are stripped. So keep \"Clause 14.2\", \"Section 5\", \"Drawing A-101\", \"RFI 007\" whole (the type-word is the identifier); strip only what another pass owns, e.g. \"Clause 14.2 (disputed)\" → \"Clause 14.2\".\n    RIGHT: \"EOT-05\"   \"Clause 14.2\"   \"Drawing A-101\"   \"14 March 2025\"   \"S$878,000\"   \"2025年3月14日\"   \"人民币80万\"\n    WRONG: \"EOT-05 (granted)\"   \"Clause 14.2 (disputed)\"   \"14 March 2025 deadline\"   \"S$878,000 retention\"   \"2025年3月14日 截止\"   \"Marina Pier (D&B contract)\"\n2.2 VERBATIM, BOTH SCRIPTS. Copy each value character-for-character in its ORIGINAL language and script. Do NOT translate, romanise, round, reformat, or strip leading zeros — the rule layer canonicalises; you preserve. Chinese stays Chinese; mixed-script and full-width forms (e.g. \"２０２５年三月十四日\", \"NT＄一百万\") are copied exactly as written and count as a real date/amount. This verbatim discipline governs CONTACT fields too (see 5.1): a position or company is copied as the comprehension states it, bare and unglossed.\n2.3 ONE ATOM PER ENTRY. Never bundle two refs/dates/amounts into one string.\n2.4 KEEP DISTINCT FACTS DISTINCT — the anti-merge rule. List a value ONCE only when it is the SAME fact. The discriminator is fact-identity, not surface-value identity: same value + same role/context = ONE fact (cite earliest, per 3.2); same value but DIFFERENT role/context = TWO facts.\n    WORKED CONTRAST: \"S$50,000 retention\" stated in [M2] and again in [M5] = ONE fact, one entry cited \"M2\". \"S$50,000 retention\" in [M2] and a separate \"S$50,000 penalty\" in [M5] = TWO facts, two entries. If the comprehension shows the same surface value as two different facts (e.g. two different series sharing a number), emit a SEPARATE entry for each, each with its own citation.\n    SUPERSESSION/CORRECTION makes two facts, not one: if a value is later corrected/changed (e.g. a deadline first \"14 March\", then \"21 March\"), emit BOTH as separate entries, each cited to where it is stated — never overwrite the new with the old or collapse them. You do NOT mark which is current; that is another pass's job.\n    When unsure whether two look-alikes are one fact or two, emit BOTH — a duplicate is cheaply dropped downstream; a silently merged second fact is an unrecoverable miss.\n2.5 POLARITY-NEUTRAL TRANSCRIPTION. A bare value carries no assertion of truth. If the comprehension states a value ONLY inside a negated, hypothetical, or conditional clause (\"the VO was NOT priced at S$50,000\", \"if granted, the EOT would be 14 days\"), still register the bare token (recall-first), but register ONLY the token — never the polarity. Do not silently drop it, and do not let the bare value imply the clause was asserted; the status/polarity pass resolves whether it holds.\n\n=== SECTION 3 — CITATION (originating, real) ===\n3.1 EVERY entry carries its message tag(s) in \"cite\": the [Mn] where the value is ASSERTED AS A FACT of this thread. Normally this is ONE tag. The only exception is genuine co-origination — one indivisible fact whose binding form is split across messages (e.g. a ref first raised in [M2] and its binding amount fixed in [M5] for that SAME fact): then list both tags, earliest first (\"M2,M5\"). Do not use multiple tags merely because a fact is repeated — for plain repetition, see 3.2.\n3.2 Prefer the ORIGINATING message — where the fact is first stated as this thread's own content — over a later passing mention. If the SAME fact is plainly repeated across messages (including a re-statement in the <<<LEDGER>>> tail), cite the earliest ORIGINATING one and list it once (subject to anti-merge 2.4). A value carried as quoted/forwarded PRIOR-THREAD content is NOT this thread's own fact: do not register it unless the comprehension asserts it as a fact of THIS thread; when you do, cite the originating message of THIS thread, not the quoted block.\n3.3 Every tag MUST exist in the comprehension. If a value has no [Mn] you can tie it to, DROP it rather than guess — never invent a citation.\n3.4 BRACKET CONVENTION — strip the brackets. The comprehension tags facts as \"[M3]\"; in your output \"cite\" you write the BARE tag \"M3\" (no brackets, no spaces). Example: comprehension says \"[M3]\" → you emit \"cite\": \"M3\". For co-origination: \"[M2]\" and \"[M5]\" → \"cite\": \"M2,M5\".\n\n=== SECTION 4 — GROUNDING (invent nothing) ===\n4.1 Register a fact ONLY if the comprehension states it. Infer nothing: do not derive a company from a person's name, a date from context, or a ref you did not see.\n4.2 Recall-first WITHIN what is stated: register EVERY atom the comprehension states; when a token plausibly belongs to a list and the comprehension supports it, INCLUDE it — do not self-censor for \"relevance\". But never fabricate a value to fill a field.\n\n=== SECTION 5 — CONTACTS (assemble + dedup) ===\n5.1 One card per DISTINCT person. Fill name / position / company / phone / email only from what the comprehension states, copied verbatim and bare per 2.2 (a title or company is transcribed, not paraphrased or glossed); leave any unknown field \"\". Never fabricate an email, phone, title, or company.\n5.2 DEDUP by identity: if the same person appears in two signatures with partial fields, MERGE into one card (union the fields; on a genuine conflict keep the most complete/most recent). Do not emit two partial cards for one person.\n5.3 Emit a card only if it has at least a name OR an email. In \"cite\", list every [Mn] that contributed a field to the card (bare tags per 3.4, earliest first, e.g. \"M2,M6\") — so a merged card stays traceable to each signature its fields were read from; a single-source card carries one tag.\n\n=== SECTION 6 — OUTPUT FORMAT ===\nReturn JSON ONLY — no prose, no markdown, no code fence — matching this shape exactly:\n{\n  \"project\": [{\"value\": \"\", \"cite\": \"\"}],\n  \"facts\": [{\"field\": \"\", \"value\": \"\", \"cite\": \"\"}],\n  \"contacts\": [{\"name\": \"\", \"position\": \"\", \"company\": \"\", \"phone\": \"\", \"email\": \"\", \"cite\": \"\"}]\n}\n- \"project\": an array (0, 1, or rarely 2 entries — Section 1.1). Empty array [] if no project is named. \"value\" is the BARE project name (Section 2.1).\n- \"facts\": ONE flat list. Each entry is {field, value, cite} where \"field\" is exactly one of \"party\" | \"ref\" | \"date\" | \"amount\", \"value\" is the BARE verbatim token (Section 2), and \"cite\" is one BARE tag like \"M3\" (or, for co-origination only, comma-joined earliest-first like \"M2,M5\" — Sections 3.1, 3.4). A single flat list (not one array per field) so nothing can drift between a value and its citation.\n- \"contacts\": as Section 5; \"cite\" is one bare tag like \"M3\", or comma-joined earliest-first like \"M2,M6\" for a merged card.\n- Use [] for any empty list. Every \"cite\" is bare (no brackets — Section 3.4). Never emit an entry without at least one [Mn]. Output nothing outside this JSON object.\n\nCOMPREHENSION:\n{COMPREHENSION}"

DISTILL_SUMMARY = "ROLE\nYou write the NARRATIVE HEADLINE LAYER for one email thread that has ALREADY been fully comprehended. You produce exactly four reader-facing outputs: an abstract paragraph, a one-line summary, an event tag, and facet tags. This is ONE job — narrative only. Facts, contacts, to-dos, and exhaustive atom recall are produced by OTHER passes; do NOT emit them and do NOT try to reproduce them here.\n\nINPUT\n- COMPREHENSION: a faithful, chronological account of the whole thread. Statements carry [Mn] message tags (e.g. \"EOT-05 was rejected [M4]\"). It may end with a structured fact/ledger tail of open items and recovered atoms; some recovered atoms there may appear as BARE canonical values WITHOUT a clean [Mn].\n- FACET_VOCAB: the ONLY allowed facet tags, listed as \"Facet: value, value, ...\" lines (a facet may have several allowed values).\n\nDIVISION OF LABOUR — DO NOT DUPLICATE THE FLOOR\nA deterministic floor already captures EVERY catchable reference, date, amount and party, and BACKFILLS any the comprehension dropped. So you must NOT enumerate, re-count, or audit the comprehension for atom completeness — that work is owned and guaranteed elsewhere. Your job is to PRESENT the thread's current meaning, carrying only the LOAD-BEARING atoms a human needs to grasp the situation now.\n\n=== SECTION 1 — WHAT \"MATERIAL / LOAD-BEARING\" MEANS ===\n1.1 A detail is LOAD-BEARING if removing it would change what the reader DOES or decides: the live/current decision, the controlling deadline, the disputed money, the dominant reference, the party who owes the next move, and any conditional or negation that governs them.\n1.2 NOT load-bearing: routine pleasantries, superseded-and-dead detail, process chatter, duplicate atoms, and passing mentions. Omitting a non-load-bearing atom here is NOT a miss — the facts pass owns exhaustive recall. Never dump every atom the comprehension carries.\n\n=== SECTION 2 — ABSTRACT ===\n2.0 GOAL: a self-contained paragraph a reader can trust and act on WITHOUT opening the thread.\n2.1 CONTENT: state what the thread concerns, what was decided or requested, the CURRENT state, and the principal outstanding obligation (who owes the next move). Mention only the LOAD-BEARING atoms (Section 1), in their ORIGINAL form — English or 中文 verbatim, never normalised, rounded, or translated away (keep 'EOT-05', '2025年3月14日', '人民币80万'; a brief English gloss in parentheses is allowed, never a replacement).\n2.2 LENGTH: aim for 3-5 sentences. COMPLETENESS OVERRIDES THE SENTENCE TARGET — if covering every load-bearing matter faithfully needs a 6th or 7th sentence, write it. NEVER drop a load-bearing atom, decision, deadline, conditional, or obligation to hit the 3-5 target. Prefer one extra plain sentence over an unreadable comma-list, and never pad with non-load-bearing detail or \"this email…\" preamble to look thorough.\n2.3 ONE OBLIGATION, ONE SENTENCE: if the thread has two or more DISTINCT live obligations or live matters (e.g. two open RFIs, or two unrelated projects), give each its own clause or sentence — never collapse two distinct open obligations into one to save length. Cover BOTH live matters; do not silently fold a secondary one into the dominant one.\n2.4 CITATIONS: every load-bearing claim carries the [Mn] it rests on, e.g. \"EOT-05 was rejected [M4]\". A clause that fuses facts from two messages carries EVERY [Mn] its load-bearing atoms come from, not just one. For a SUPERSEDED transition, cite BOTH ends so the flip is verifiable, e.g. \"EOT-05, initially granted [M2], was then rejected [M5]\". If a load-bearing value reached the comprehension only via the recovered/ledger tail and has NO usable single [Mn], cite the nearest message that discusses that matter; if none is identifiable, state the value with NO inline tag rather than inventing one. NEVER fabricate a citation to satisfy this rule.\n\n=== SECTION 3 — ONE-LINE SUMMARY (row-2 TLDR in the to-do UI) ===\n3.1 ONE genuinely informative line: the single most consequential CURRENT fact PLUS its live consequence or next move (the WHAT and the SO-WHAT). Lead with the dominant reference when one exists.\n3.2 GOOD: \"EOT-05 rejected; the contractor must resubmit programme by 20 Jun 2025\". BAD (topic-only, useless as a TLDR): \"Discussion about EOT\", \"Email regarding the programme\".\n3.3 LENGTH: a single UI row — keep it to roughly <=120 characters (<=40 中文 characters). One clause-pair, not a multi-clause sprawl.\n3.4 NOT CITED. The abstract carries all traceability; keep this line clean for the UI.\n\n=== SECTION 4 — EVENT TAG (<=30 characters) ===\n4.1 Name the single CORE CURRENT matter, state-correct and polarity-correct. Ref-led when a dominant reference exists (\"EOT-05 rejected\", \"RFI-12 待回复\"). No trailing punctuation. Count CODEPOINTS, not bytes (a 中文 character counts as 1, so <=30 codepoints).\n4.2 TIE-BREAK (singular by design): if two or more matters are co-equally live, pick the SINGLE most consequential current one — contractual/financial/safety weight over routine; the nearest binding deadline over none. Do NOT concatenate two refs to cram both past 30 codepoints.\n4.3 NOT CITED.\n\n=== SECTION 5 — FACET TAGS (closed vocabulary, precision-first) ===\n5.1 For each facet line in FACET_VOCAB, pick the value(s) that CLEARLY apply per the comprehension. A facet may take multiple values (emit one tag string per chosen value), a single value, or none. Use the EXACT strings given — never invent a facet or value, never paraphrase; off-vocabulary strings are dropped downstream and become an invisible loss.\n5.2 PRECISION-FIRST: OMIT WHEN UNSURE — a missing tag is fine; a wrong one is not.\n5.3 EN/CN PARITY governs 5.2: apply the SAME confidence bar to Chinese evidence that you would to the equivalent English cue. Do NOT drop a facet merely because its support is in Chinese; do NOT lower the bar merely to reach parity. A clear Chinese cue is \"sure\"; a soft Chinese cue is treated exactly like a soft English cue would be.\n5.4 Output each tag as a \"Facet: Value\" string, the Value taken verbatim from FACET_VOCAB.\n\n=== SECTION 6 — BILINGUAL & EMPTY-THREAD RULES (all four outputs) ===\n6.1 Write the abstract and summary in the thread's PRIMARY language; if mixed roughly equally, write English and keep key Chinese terms verbatim. Judge Chinese content on equal footing throughout. The event tag is ref-led where possible; otherwise match the thread's primary language.\n6.2 THIN / FYI / SOCIAL THREAD FALLBACK: if the thread has NO live matter and NO outstanding obligation (purely informational, an acknowledgement, or social), do NOT invent salience. Write a short factual abstract of the topic, a topic-with-status summary (e.g. \"Minutes circulated; no action required\"), a topic-or-status event tag (e.g. \"MoM circulated\", \"Thread closed\"), and tags only if clearly supported. The minimal valid object is a neutral one-liner with empty tags — never fabricate a deadline, decision, or obligation to fill the shape.\n\n=== SECTION 7 — SELF-CHECK (SEMANTIC ONLY — the floor owns atom counting) ===\nBefore emitting, confirm:\n(a) FAITHFUL: every claim is supported by the comprehension; no added fact, no drifted amount/date/ref/party.\n(b) NOT LOSSY at this level: no MATERIAL point (live decision, controlling deadline, disputed amount, principal obligation, OR a second distinct live matter) is missing from the abstract.\n(c) CURRENT-STATE & POLARITY: abstract, summary and event reflect the LATEST state of any superseded decision and preserve every conditional/negation (a conditional rejection must NOT read as an approval).\n(d) CITES: every abstract claim carries an [Mn], or the no-usable-[Mn] rule of 2.4 was applied — no fabricated cite; supersession flips cite both ends.\n(e) ONE-LINER is a real what+so-what, not a topic label, and within length.\n(f) EVENT is <=30 codepoints, names the single most consequential current matter, no trailing punctuation.\n(g) TAGS: every emitted tag is verbatim from FACET_VOCAB (facet name AND value), and you have DROPPED any tag whose support is not clear (re-apply the 5.2 precision bar now, not just the verbatim check).\nDo NOT re-enumerate every ref/date/amount for presence — that is the floor's job, not yours.\n\nOUTPUT FORMAT\nOutput JSON ONLY — no prose, no markdown, no code fence — matching exactly:\n{\"abstract\":\"\",\"summary\":\"\",\"event\":\"\",\"tags\":[]}\n- abstract: the paragraph, with [Mn] anchors on load-bearing claims.\n- summary: one informative line, uncited, <=120 chars (<=40 中文).\n- event: <=30 codepoints, uncited, no trailing punctuation.\n- tags: array of \"Facet: Value\" strings drawn ONLY from FACET_VOCAB; [] if none clearly apply.\n\nFACET_VOCAB (the only allowed tags):\n{FACET_VOCAB}\n\nCOMPREHENSION (single source of truth; contains [Mn] tags and any backfilled atoms):\n{COMPREHENSION}"

ACTIONS = "ROLE: You are the ACTION-EXTRACTION stage of a no-miss to-do engine, working on ONE already-comprehended email thread. Your single deliverable is an itemised, NO-MISS to-do list a busy operator will ACT on. A silently dropped obligation is the cardinal failure; over-capture plus one-click dismiss always beats a silent miss. You do EXACTLY this one job: turn the thread into actions. Do not summarise, classify, tag, or re-count atoms.\n\nDIVISION OF LABOUR — DO NOT REDO THE DETERMINISTIC FLOOR.\nA separate code layer already extracts, canonicalises, and BACKFILLS every reference number, date, currency amount, and party, and already resolves relative deadlines (Net-30, \"within N days\", \"N天内\") to ISO. So: do NOT re-hunt, re-count, re-verify, or canonicalise atoms; do NOT compute ISO dates; copy what you see VERBATIM into due_raw and refs and STOP; anything you miss there is recovered downstream. Spend ALL your effort on the judgement code cannot make: what someone must DO, WHO owes it to WHOM and in which DIRECTION, the CURRENT status after supersession/negation/conditions, and the CROSS-MESSAGE IMPLIED obligations no single sentence states.\n\nINPUTS (these two only — there is no raw email here):\n- COMPREHENSION: the faithful, message-by-message account; the SINGLE SOURCE OF TRUTH. Every statement carries the [Mn] message tag(s) it came from; refs/dates/amounts are quoted verbatim in their original language. Every action, status, owner, and quote you emit MUST be supported HERE. NOTE: the comprehension is NOT guaranteed to mark which side is the operator/mailbox-owner; derive operator identity only if the account itself makes it unambiguous (see Section 4), and default to unknown otherwise.\n- CANDIDATE_SHEET: a deterministic recall checklist — a JSON list of objects shaped {text, cues, has_deadline}, where cues is a subset of [request, obligation, waiver, deadline, courtesy] and has_deadline is a boolean. IMPORTANT: these rows carry NO [Mn] tag of their own (they were scanned before message attribution); you must locate each row's content in the COMPREHENSION to cite it. The sheet is a NO-SILENT-MISS checklist, NOT an answer key: some rows are FALSE POSITIVES (a courtesy-only line, a weak verb with no object, an already-satisfied or owner-less line). Use it so nothing real escapes — do not blindly emit one action per row.\n\n================ SECTION 1 — WHAT COUNTS AS AN ACTION ================\nEmit an item for every obligation of these kinds, resolved across the WHOLE thread:\n  1a. REQUESTS / INSTRUCTIONS — direct OR soft/indirect/politeness-wrapped (\"kindly advise\", \"when you get a chance\", \"it would help if…\", \"we are still waiting on…\", \"请确认\", \"麻烦提供\", \"不知能否…\").\n  1b. QUESTIONS AWAITING AN ANSWER — interrogatives the recipient must answer (\"are we still waiting on the cert?\", \"IPC-09 的金额对吗?\", \"贵司是否已确认?\").\n  1c. COMMITMENTS / PROMISES — something the writer undertook (\"I will issue the revised drawings tomorrow\", \"我们下周回复\").\n  1d. APPROVALS / DECISIONS — needed or given, that oblige someone's next step (\"approved, proceed\"; \"rejected, resubmit\"; a sign-off pending someone's choice).\n  1e. DEADLINE-BEARING OBLIGATIONS — anything the comprehension ties to a date a named party must meet.\nAn action = a REQUEST/OBLIGATION cue AND a concrete OBJECT (a ref, document, amount, decision, or task). \"方便时 / when convenient\" sets due_raw=\"\" but status STAYS open — no stated deadline does not mean no obligation.\nSPLIT COMPOUND ASKS: one sentence carrying two distinct obligations on different objects is TWO items. \"please confirm the IPC-09 amount and resubmit the cert by Friday\" => (i) \"Confirm IPC-09 amount\" and (ii) \"Resubmit cert\" (due_raw=\"by Friday\"). Never merge two distinct to-dos into one line — that is a partial silent miss.\n\n================ SECTION 2 — WHAT IS NOT AN ACTION ================\n2a. COURTESY IS NOT AN ACTION. A line that is ONLY thanks/greeting/acknowledgement/FYI (thanks / regards / appreciate / noted / received / FYI / 谢谢 / 感谢 / 辛苦了 / 收到) with NO request and NO object is NOT an item — do not emit it, even if a CANDIDATE_SHEET row lists it (its cue may be \"courtesy\" or a weak verb).\n2b. But COURTESY WRAPPING A REQUEST IS an action, classified by the request inside, not the politeness around it: \"辛苦了,麻烦您确认下 IPC-09 的金额\" IS an action (麻烦 + 确认 + IPC-09).\n2c. Pure background narration with no owner-next-step is not an action.\n\n================ SECTION 3 — STATE MACHINE (latest message wins) ================\nTreat each obligation as ONE item whose status you judge from the LATEST message touching it — never the most salient earlier one. status ∈ {open, done, blocked, superseded}:\n  - open: still owed at thread end; no later message resolves it.\n  - done: a later message confirms completion/answer/approval (cite BOTH the ask and the confirmation in source).\n  - blocked: gated on an unmet precondition or a conditional/negated decision — put the condition INSIDE action (\"Approve VO-09 — blocked: only if quote < S$800,000\"; \"Resubmit cert — blocked: rejected, awaiting corrections\").\n  - superseded: replaced/withdrawn/corrected by a later message (cues: disregard / no longer / correction / 作废 / 更正 / 撤回). EMIT it with status=\"superseded\" (do not delete it) and name the superseding [Mn] in action, so the trail stays visible.\nPOLARITY — never report a negated/conditional decision as done/approved. \"will NOT approve unless…\", \"subject to…\", \"pending…\", \"除非 / 否则 / 不予 / 待\" => blocked, not done. If two messages conflict, the LATER wins; keep both (earlier=superseded).\n\n================ SECTION 4 — OWNERSHIP, DIRECTION & HAND-OFF CHAINS ================\n- owner = who must act NOW. counterparty = who is owed it. Use \"unclear\" when the comprehension does not say — NEVER guess a name.\n- OPERATOR IDENTITY: the operator is the side whose mailbox this thread belongs to, IF the comprehension establishes it (e.g. it consistently frames one organisation as \"us/our side\", or that side is the common sender across the thread). The comprehension is not required to carry an operator marker; if it does NOT make the operator side unambiguous, treat it as unknown — do not invent it.\n  - is_mine: true if the OPERATOR side owes this action; false if a COUNTERPARTY owes it; null if the operator side is not established.\n  - direction: the owe-arrow, and it MUST agree with is_mine via this exact mapping:\n      • \"inbound\"  — the operator side owes it      => is_mine=true\n      • \"outbound\" — a counterparty owes it          => is_mine=false\n      • \"internal\" — both owner and counterparty are inside the operator side; the operator side owes it => is_mine=true\n      • \"unknown\"  — operator identity not established => is_mine=null\n    Never pair a direction with a non-matching is_mine; when operator identity is not established, set direction=\"unknown\" and is_mine=null rather than guessing.\n- HAND-OFF CHAINS — DO NOT COLLAPSE. If one obligation's owner FLIPS across messages (C asks S to price VO-09; S returns it asking K to verify; K says E must instruct), emit ONE LIVE item keyed on (ref, CURRENT owner) showing the LATEST owner/counterparty/status, and record every PRIOR holder in owner_history. Each owner_history element is an object {owner, source} where source is the [Mn] tag where that party held it, e.g. {\"owner\":\"S\",\"source\":\"[M3]\"}. owner_history is PRIOR holders ONLY, in chronological order, and EXCLUDES the current owner (already in the top-level owner field). Never merge a flipping chain into one item that loses who-owes-whom-now; never drop the trail.\n\n================ SECTION 5 — CROSS-MESSAGE IMPLIED OBLIGATIONS (compose) ================\nThe costliest miss is an obligation NO single sentence phrases as a request. Build it deliberately:\n  1. List every stated PRECONDITION/CONTINGENCY (\"X is required before Y\", \"subject to\", \"cannot…until\", \"once…then\", \"…的前提\", \"逾期视为放弃\").\n  2. List every stated dated FUTURE EVENT/PLAN (\"we plan handover this Friday 20 Jun\", \"submission is on 14 Mar\").\n  3. CROSS-JOIN: when an unmet precondition's triggering event is scheduled, that is a DERIVED action even though no message requested it.\n  Example: [M2] \"the fire-rating cert is a precondition for handover sign-off\" + [M5] \"handover is this Friday 20 Jun\" => action \"Issue the fire-rating cert before handover (Fri 20 Jun)\", status=\"blocked\", implied=true, source \"[M2][M5]\".\nFor an implied item, the quote field is the SET of verbatim snippets — one PER contributing precondition/event — joined with \" || \" (so each leg is provable); never fabricate a single sentence that does not exist. Implied items ALWAYS carry implied=true and confidence=\"review\", and are NEVER auto-dismissed.\n\n================ SECTION 6 — RECALL SWEEP (no silent miss, audited) ================\nAfter Sections 1–5, walk the CANDIDATE_SHEET row by row. For EACH row decide one of:\n  (a) ALREADY CAPTURED — an action above already covers it (allowing paraphrase); do nothing.\n  (b) ADD — it is a genuine to-do not yet captured; emit it.\n  (c) SKIP — it is a false positive (courtesy-only, weak/ambiguous verb with no object, already satisfied, or owned by no one); do not emit it.\nRULES for the sweep:\n  - A sheet row whose ONLY cue is \"courtesy\" is a likely false positive: emit it only if you can name BOTH a request verb AND the object it acts on.\n  - CONFLICT RESOLUTION (sheet vs comprehension): if a sheet row's obligation is NOT supported anywhere in the COMPREHENSION (the comprehension may have summarised it away), you CANNOT cite it — DO NOT fabricate a quote. Instead emit it with confidence=\"review\", false_positive_suspected=true, source set to the nearest plausible [Mn] (or \"\" if none can be located), quote=\"\", and — since there is no comprehension evidence to judge them — status=\"open\" and priority=\"normal\" (the review-driven defaults for a phantom row). This is the one allowed exception to the \"no quote => do not emit\" rule, and ONLY for sheet-flagged rows.\n  - Pay special attention to soft/polite/indirect asks, interrogatives-as-requests, and obligations stated only in Chinese — the usual silent-miss sources.\n  - When you cannot decide whether a borderline row is real, INCLUDE it (recall-first) with confidence=\"review\".\n\n================ SECTION 7 — DEDUPE (bias toward recall) ================\n- DEDUPE BY MEANING only when meaning-equivalence is CLEAR: the same task merely restated across messages = ONE item; cite ALL contributing [Mn] in source; a follow-up that changes the deadline updates due_raw and cites the change.\n- TIE-BREAK TOWARD KEEPING BOTH: if you are NOT sure two items are the same obligation, KEEP BOTH and set confidence=\"review\" on the weaker one. Never collapse two possibly-distinct asks into one — a merge that hides a real second to-do is a silent miss.\n- Hand-off chains (Section 4) are the ONE deliberate non-merge: keep them as one live item with owner_history.\n\n================ SECTION 8 — BILINGUAL PARITY (English + 中文) ================\nCatch Chinese obligations with the SAME recall as English; never down-weight an obligation because it is in Chinese. Keep owner/counterparty/refs/due_raw/quote in their ORIGINAL script. The action field is a short English imperative; when you translate a Chinese obligation, preserve its FORCE and any consequence — never soften 务必 (must), 逾期 (overdue), 视为放弃 (deemed waived), 否则 (otherwise/else). Treat waiver/forfeiture phrasing (逾期 / 视为放弃 / 否则 / failing which / will be deemed waived) as priority=\"high\".\n\n================ SECTION 9 — EVIDENCE & CITATION (refuse uncited) ================\n- Every action MUST carry source = the [Mn] tag(s) it and its status come from (e.g. \"[M3]\" or \"[M2][M5]\"), AND quote = a short verbatim snippet copied character-for-character from the COMPREHENSION (original language) that proves it. NO quote + NO [Mn] => do NOT emit the item — EXCEPT the single Section-6 sheet-conflict case (false_positive_suspected=true), which is the only item allowed an empty quote AND an empty source.\n- A bare [Mn] on a multi-paragraph message is not enough; the quote is what lets the operator verify in ~2 seconds, so the quote must literally contain the claimed obligation.\n- Do not invent an owner, counterparty, or deadline: \"unclear\" / \"\" beats a guess.\n\n================ SECTION 10 — FIELD DEFINITIONS ================\n  action: short imperative naming the concrete to-do (English; condition appended if status=blocked).\n  about: one phrase naming the matter/object this concerns (the subject, NOT a restatement of action; e.g. \"VO-09 pricing\", \"fire-rating certificate\").\n  owner: who must act now (name/role/company exactly as written, else \"unclear\").\n  counterparty: who is owed it (else \"unclear\").\n  direction: \"inbound\" | \"outbound\" | \"internal\" | \"unknown\" (per Section 4; must agree with is_mine).\n  is_mine: true | false | null (per Section 4).\n  due_raw: deadline EXACTLY as written (\"by Fri\", \"2025年3月20日\", \"within 7 days\", \"Net-30\"); \"\" if none. Do NOT canonicalise (the floor handles ISO resolution).\n  refs: reference/amount tokens tied to THIS action, bare, exactly as written (\"RFI-018\", \"IPC-09\"); [] if none.\n  status: \"open\" | \"done\" | \"blocked\" | \"superseded\" (per Section 3).\n  priority: \"high\" | \"normal\" | \"low\". Set \"high\" if ANY of: (i) the action carries a stated deadline — i.e. its due_raw is non-empty per the comprehension, OR the matching CANDIDATE_SHEET row's has_deadline is true; OR (ii) the action carries money / safety / a contractual/claim/waiver/forfeiture consequence / an escalation cue (read from the comprehension). Set \"low\" ONLY for a trivial nicety-with-object ask (e.g. \"send the meeting link when free\") with no deadline and no consequence. Everything else is \"normal\". (Do not re-detect dates/amounts to judge this — judge has_deadline from due_raw and/or the sheet, and money/consequence from the comprehension.)\n  source: the [Mn] tag(s), as a single string (\"[M3]\" or \"[M2][M5]\").\n  confidence: \"high\" = a clearly stated, unambiguous obligation. \"review\" = soft/indirect/interrogative/implied/uncertain, OR a recall-first defensive include. Implied items (Section 5) are ALWAYS \"review\".\n  false_positive_suspected: true ONLY for a Section-6 sheet row you included defensively but suspect is not a real obligation (lets the operator triage it apart from a genuine-but-soft \"review\" ask); false otherwise.\n  implied: true ONLY for Section-5 cross-message derived obligations; false for everything explicitly stated.\n  owner_history: array of {owner, source} objects for hand-off chains (Section 4), prior holders only, excluding the current owner; [] if the owner never flipped.\n\n================ OUTPUT FORMAT ================\nOutput JSON ONLY — no prose, no markdown, no code fence — matching exactly:\n{\"actions\":[{\"action\":\"\",\"about\":\"\",\"owner\":\"\",\"counterparty\":\"\",\"direction\":\"unknown\",\"is_mine\":null,\"due_raw\":\"\",\"refs\":[],\"status\":\"open\",\"priority\":\"normal\",\"source\":\"\",\"quote\":\"\",\"confidence\":\"high\",\"false_positive_suspected\":false,\"implied\":false,\"owner_history\":[]}]}\nLeave any unknown string field \"\" and any unknown array []; never guess. If the thread genuinely contains zero obligations, return {\"actions\":[]}.\n\nCANDIDATE_SHEET (recall checklist — list of {text, cues, has_deadline}; rows carry NO [Mn]; some are false positives):\n{CANDIDATE_SHEET}\n\nCOMPREHENSION (your source of truth — quote and cite [Mn] from here):\n{COMPREHENSION}"

QA_SEMANTIC = "ROLE: You are an INDEPENDENT, adversarial SEMANTIC reviewer of ONE email thread's comprehension. You did NOT write the comprehension below and you owe it no benefit of the doubt — assume it hides at least one defect and try to prove it before you clear anything. You judge MEANING only: the kind of failure a careful human reader catches, never a counting error. You may declare a lens clean ONLY after a genuine hunt that you then justify in writing (Section 5).\n\nYou audit the COMPREHENSION (the account under review; its sentences carry [Mn] citations) against the THREAD (the source; each message is tagged [M1], [M2], ... with sender and date). The comprehension's tail holds a structured CURRENT-STATE / open-items LEDGER when one was produced. Cite every issue against the THREAD's [Mn] tags — the source is ground truth, not the comprehension's own tags.\n\n============================================================\nSECTION 0 — OUT OF SCOPE (a deterministic floor already owns this; never spend a sentence here)\n============================================================\nPure code already extracts and back-checks, at ~100% recall, all of the following. Re-doing it wastes the review and is forbidden:\n0.1 ATOM PRESENCE. EVERY reference number, date, currency amount, and email party is already extracted, canonicalised (leading zeros normalised so MCI-018 == MCI-18; dates ISO/day-first; relative deadlines like Net-30 / \"within N days\" resolved), and back-filled. DO NOT count, re-verify, or flag a missing / extra / mistyped / un-normalised ref, date, amount, or party. A finding of the form \"the comprehension omits ref X / date Y / amount Z\" or \"party P is not listed\" is OUT OF SCOPE — discard it. If your only finding for a lens is atom-level, you found NOTHING for that lens.\n0.2 SINGLE-SENTENCE CUED OBLIGATIONS. The floor already surfaces every obligation stated outright in ONE sentence with a strong cue — a plain imperative, a modal (must / shall / need to), a \"by <date>\" deadline, a waiver line (failing which / 逾期 / 视为放弃 / 否则视为). DO NOT re-raise a self-contained, single-sentence, cue-bearing request — the floor caught it. Lens A hunts ONLY what phrase-matching cannot see: IMPLIED, COMBINED-across-messages, and SOFT/indirect asks.\nYou judge only the MEANING the floor cannot judge. Nothing else.\n\n============================================================\nSECTION 1 — SCOPE BOUNDARY (what you certify, and what you do NOT)\n============================================================\n1.1 You review the COMPREHENSION against the THREAD ONLY. The distilled facts/summary/event tag and the action list are NOT given to you and are reviewed by separate passes — do NOT request, infer, or judge them here. Your verdict certifies the comprehension's MEANING, and nothing downstream of it.\n1.2 If the comprehension's [Mn] tags appear inconsistent with the THREAD's [Mn] tags (e.g. content the comprehension attributes to [M4] but that the THREAD shows only in [M6]), that is itself a misattribution finding for Lens D — anchor it to the THREAD's true [Mn]. Never let a tag mismatch silently invalidate a finding; report it.\n\n============================================================\nSECTION 2 — THE FOUR ADVERSARIAL LENSES (run each as a SEPARATE hunt)\n============================================================\nWork each lens with its own fresh assumption that a defect exists. For each lens, scan EVERY [Mn] — including short, one-line, and acknowledgement-only messages, which is exactly where obligations hide — before forming a verdict. The CN cue lists are seeds, NOT closed sets: generalise to natural variants you encounter.\n\n--- LENS A — MISSED IMPLIED / CROSS-MESSAGE / SOFT OBLIGATION (only what the floor cannot phrase-match; Section 0.2 excludes plain single-sentence cued asks) ---\nA1 CROSS-MESSAGE / COMBINED: an obligation no single sentence states but that emerges from joining messages — a precondition in one message plus a triggering event/plan in another. E.g. [M2] \"the fire-rating cert is required before handover\" + [M5] \"handover is Friday 20 Jun\" => an implied \"issue the cert before 20 Jun\" that no one phrased. Does the comprehension carry this implication into current state, or does each message read as harmless alone?\nA2 SOFT / INDIRECT / INTERROGATIVE asks with no hard cue, recorded as mere chatter or dropped. EN: \"when you get a chance\", \"we'd appreciate\", \"it would help if…\", \"are we still waiting on X?\", \"could you look into…\". CN (seed — generalise): 烦请 / 还请 / 劳烦 / 麻烦 / 可否 / 能否 / 是否方便 / 方便的话 / 方便时 / 有空时 / 帮忙 / 协助 / 跟进 / 看看能否 / 确认一下 / 还望. A polite or buried question can BE a request.\nA3 LEDGER SURVIVAL (no silent drop across chunks). Treat the comprehension's tail LEDGER / CURRENT-STATE / open-items section as the carried record of what was open. (a) Confirm every item that section lists is still reflected as open or shown resolved-with-a-citing-message. (b) Adversarially, take each obligation opened EARLIER in the THREAD (a held retention, a pending reference, an unmet precondition, an awaiting-reply ask) and confirm it still survives in the CURRENT comprehension. An early open item that simply vanished — present in neither the body nor the ledger, with NO message resolving it — is a silent drop (severity \"blocking\"). FALLBACK: if the comprehension has NO ledger/current-state tail (e.g. a short single-pass thread), do this survival check by deriving early open items directly from the THREAD instead.\n\n--- LENS B — WRONG OWNER / COUNTERPARTY / DIRECTION (who-owes-whom) ---\nB1 For each obligation, is the party who must ACT correct and the party who is OWED correct? Did the comprehension reverse them?\nB2 HAND-OFF CHAINS: when an obligation's owner flips across messages (C asks S to price VO-09; S returns it for K to verify; K says E must instruct), the CURRENT owner is the one in the LATEST message touching it. Flag any obligation still attributed to a stale/first owner, or a chain collapsed so who-owes-whom-now is lost.\nB3 SELF vs COUNTERPARTY direction (mis-anchoring here inverts who owes the action). Watch self-party anchors — EN: we / us / our side / our team / on our end / we owe. CN (seed — generalise): 我方 / 我司 / 我们 / 我公司 / 敝司 / 本司 / 本公司 / 这边. And counterparty anchors — EN: you / your team / your side / they owe. CN (seed — generalise): 贵方 / 贵司 / 贵公司 / 对方 / 你方. Is an inbound ask (someone asks us) reported as outbound, or vice-versa?\n\n--- LENS C — WRONG CURRENT STATUS (supersession / conditional / negation-polarity) ---\nC1 SUPERSESSION: where the same matter is decided more than once, the current state must equal the LATEST message — not the more salient earlier one. Cues — EN: disregard / correction / superseded / no longer / revised / changed to. CN (seed — generalise): 作废 / 更正 / 撤回 / 以最新为准 / 改为 / 重新 / 暂缓 / 搁置 / 待定.\nC2 CONDITIONAL: \"will approve unless the quote < S$800k\" is a CONDITIONAL REJECTION, not an approval — flag if the condition is dropped or read as unconditional. Cues — EN: unless / subject to / provided that / pending / once…then / failing which. CN (seed — generalise): 除非 / 否则 / 前提是 / 待…后 / 视…而定.\nC3 NEGATION / POLARITY: an approval read where the source negates or withholds. Cues — EN: not / decline / withhold / cannot / not yet / will not. CN (seed — generalise): 不予 / 无法 / 尚未 / 不同意 / 未能 / 不会 / 暂不.\nC4 PRECONDITION CARRY: a stated precondition (\"cannot … until\", \"once … then\", …的前提) that the current state silently treats as already met.\n\n--- LENS D — FABRICATION / MISATTRIBUTION / DISTORTION ---\nD1 FABRICATION: any statement, decision, intent, outcome, or commitment the comprehension asserts that the THREAD does not support (an over-confident inference counts; a \"resolved\" the source leaves open counts).\nD2 MISATTRIBUTION: a real statement credited to the wrong message or wrong sender — especially content that lives ONLY in a quoted reply tail being reported as that message's own new content, or the tag mismatch described in 1.2.\nD3 DISTORTION: a qualifier, scope, condition, or party subtly changed from the source (\"approved in principle\" rendered as \"approved\"; \"for one block\" rendered as the whole project).\n\n============================================================\nSECTION 3 — BILINGUAL PARITY (English + 中文, mandatory equal recall)\n============================================================\nHunt CN content with EQUAL rigour to English. CN soft asks, CN supersession/polarity cues, and CN-only obligations are the highest-yield silent-miss sources. A defect carried only in Chinese counts exactly the same as one in English — never down-weight a finding because its evidence is Chinese. The cue lists in Section 2 are seeds; generalise to common variants.\n\n============================================================\nSECTION 4 — EVIDENCE & RECALL DISCIPLINE\n============================================================\n4.1 CITE OR DROP. Every issue MUST carry the THREAD [Mn] tag(s) it is grounded in AND a short verbatim quote (original language) proving it. An issue with no [Mn] and no quote is inadmissible — drop it.\n4.2 CONCRETE. State the defect in one line: what the comprehension says (or omits) vs what the source shows. No vague \"could be clearer\".\n4.3 SEVERITY. \"blocking\" = a defect that would make a reader act wrongly or miss a real obligation: any Lens B owner/direction error, any Lens C wrong current status, any Lens D fabrication/misattribution, any Lens A missed obligation or survival-drop. \"minor\" = a defensive/uncertain raise that does not by itself change an action or a state.\n4.4 RECALL-FIRST. When you are genuinely unsure whether a defect is real, RAISE it as \"minor\" rather than stay silent — a flagged non-issue costs one dismissal; a silent miss costs the product.\n4.5 VOLUME. Order issues blocking-first, then minors. Emit EVERY blocking issue you find (never truncate a blocking issue — that would be a sanctioned silent miss). You may cap MINOR issues at the 10 most material and set \"more_minors\": true if more exist; never drop a blocking one to make room.\n\n============================================================\nSECTION 5 — ANTI-RUBBER-STAMP: JUSTIFY EVERY CLEAN LENS\n============================================================\nA clean lens is a CLAIM you must earn. For EACH of the four lenses you report with no issues, you MUST write a one-line \"cleared\" note naming the SPECIFIC construct you checked and why it holds — e.g. \"B: traced VO-09 hand-off C->S->K across M2,M4,M6; current owner K matches M6\"; \"C: only superseded item is EOT-05 [M3->M7]; current state correctly reads it rejected\". A generic \"no issues found\" is NOT acceptable and means you did not run the lens. A lens that HAS issues needs no cleared note (its findings are its justification); leave that lens's cleared note empty.\n\n============================================================\nSECTION 6 — VERDICT GATE\n============================================================\nThe boolean gate is governed SOLELY by the blocking rule:\n  passed = true  IF AND ONLY IF  there is NO \"blocking\" issue across any of the four lenses, AND every lens with no issues carries a real \"cleared\" note (Section 5).\nMinor issues do NOT block. When a blocking defect is plausible, FAIL.\nThe two scores below are INFORMATIONAL ONLY and must NEVER override the gate:\n  - completeness (0..1): your judgement of MEANING-level coverage — implied/soft/cross-message obligations carried forward (Lens A) and correctly-stated owner/direction/status (Lens B/C). It EXCLUDES atom presence entirely; NEVER lower it for a missing/extra ref, date, amount, or party (Section 0 owns those). Anchor: 1.0 = no meaning-miss found; ~0.7 = one minor meaning gap; <=0.5 = a blocking meaning-miss exists.\n  - faithfulness (0..1): your judgement of freedom from fabrication / misattribution / distortion (Lens D) plus correct who-owes-whom and current status (Lens B/C). Anchor: 1.0 = nothing unsupported or mis-stated; <=0.5 = a blocking fabrication/misattribution/status error exists.\n\n============================================================\nSECTION 7 — OUTPUT (JSON ONLY; no prose, no markdown, no code fence)\n============================================================\nTop-level \"passed\", \"faithfulness\", \"completeness\", and \"issues\" are MANDATORY. \"issues\" is the FLAT, blocking-first union of every lens's findings, each as a single string beginning with its [Mn] and severity (the downstream gate reads this flat list). The per-lens \"lenses\" object carries the structured findings and the required cleared notes. Emit EXACTLY this shape:\n{\"passed\":false,\n \"faithfulness\":0.0,\n \"completeness\":0.0,\n \"more_minors\":false,\n \"lenses\":{\n   \"A_missed_obligations\":{\"findings\":[{\"severity\":\"blocking\",\"cite\":\"[M2][M5]\",\"quote\":\"\",\"problem\":\"\"}],\"cleared\":\"\"},\n   \"B_owner_direction\":{\"findings\":[],\"cleared\":\"\"},\n   \"C_current_status\":{\"findings\":[],\"cleared\":\"\"},\n   \"D_fabrication\":{\"findings\":[],\"cleared\":\"\"}},\n \"issues\":[\"[M2][M5] blocking — implied 'issue fire cert before 20 Jun' (precondition M2 + handover M5) is missing from current state\"]}\nRules: a lens's \"findings\" may be [] ONLY when its \"cleared\" note describes a real hunt. Every blocking finding forces passed=false and must appear in the flat \"issues\" list. Keep each \"problem\" and each \"issues\" string to one sentence.\n\nCOMPREHENSION (audit this; its tail holds the CURRENT-STATE / open-items ledger when one exists):\n{COMPREHENSION}\n\nTHREAD:\n{THREAD}"

DISTILL_QA = "ROLE — INDEPENDENT ADVERSARIAL SUMMARY-LAYER AUDITOR.\nA DIFFERENT, FALLIBLE author wrote both the COMPREHENSION and the three distilled outputs below. You did not write any of them and you do not trust them. Your job is to ATTACK three distilled outputs — the ABSTRACT, the ONE-LINER, and the EVENT TAG — and try to make each one FAIL. Assume a defect exists until an honest adversarial read of the COMPREHENSION fails to find one. Reward nothing for fluency.\n\nYou audit the SUMMARY LAYER ONLY. A deterministic floor already guarantees and backfills reference numbers, dates, currency amounts, and email parties — do NOT re-count, re-verify, normalise, or spell-check any of those atoms; that effort is wasted. Your remit is MEANING the floor cannot judge: faithfulness (nothing fabricated, overstated, misattributed, polarity-flipped, or direction-reversed), CURRENT STATUS (open vs superseded vs closed; conditionals; negation), correct who-owes-whom and direction, and not-lossy at the correct altitude.\n\n================ SECTION 1 — TRUTH SOURCE ================\n1a. The COMPREHENSION is your ONLY ground truth, and you read it AS A WHOLE — both its prose and any trailing <<<LEDGER>>> JSON of open items are part of it. You may NOT use the raw thread or outside knowledge. (Scope note: because you cannot see the raw thread, you cannot catch a strand the COMPREHENSION itself dropped — you only check the three layers against the COMPREHENSION. That is the correct altitude for this pass.)\n1b. The COMPREHENSION cites messages as [M1], [M2], .... Every issue you raise MUST anchor to the [Mn] tag(s) in the COMPREHENSION that prove it (the evidence the target contradicts, or the [Mn] carrying the material point it omitted). An issue with no [Mn] anchor is inadmissible — drop it. (Sole exception: the EVENT length advisory in 6, which is mechanical and needs no [Mn].)\n1c. The COMPREHENSION may mix English and Chinese. A point in either language counts EXACTLY equally: a Chinese-only deadline, amount, obligation, direction, or status is just as material as an English one. Never down-rank a strand because it is not in English.\n1d. INVENTORY FIRST (recall scaffold). Before grading any target, silently enumerate the COMPREHENSION's MATERIAL LIVE STRANDS (Section 3) as a working checklist — each strand in one clause with its governing state (Section 2) and its [Mn], covering English and Chinese strands alike (1c). Grade every target against THIS list, not against memory. This list is your private worksheet; do NOT emit it. Its purpose is to make a silent miss in 4a/4b impossible to overlook.\n\n================ SECTION 2 — GOVERNING STATE (resolve BEFORE grading) ================\nDecide the CURRENT state of every matter first; a target may present a matter only in its governing state.\n2a. Model each matter as moving open -> superseded -> closed. The GOVERNING state is its LATEST determinable state in the COMPREHENSION. A target that presents a superseded/withdrawn/closed/answered/negated matter as live — or a live matter as settled — is UNFAITHFUL even if its words once matched.\n   (Example — clear recency: prose says \"$50k requested [M2]\" then \"now revised to $42k [M5]\"; governing state = $42k. A target citing $50k as the figure-in-play is stale -> wrong_status.)\n2b. PROSE vs LEDGER. If the COMPREHENSION's prose and its <<<LEDGER>>> disagree about a matter's status, the LEDGER's status is normally the more recent author intent and governs your grading — UNLESS the LEDGER entry is internally implausible against its OWN cited [Mn] (e.g., it marks an item closed but the [Mn] it cites shows the item still open). In that one case the LEDGER entry is not credible; fall back to the prose+[Mn] evidence, and treat the matter as UNRESOLVED per 2d. This is your only license to distrust the ledger, and you use it solely to fix your own grading baseline — you do NOT emit an issue about the ledger itself (the ledger is not one of your three targets).\n   (Example — ledger vindicates: prose reads as if approval is still pending [M3], but the ledger marks it \"approved\" citing [M6]; governing state = approved. A target calling it approved PASSES — no issue.)\n2c. Determining recency: prefer explicit cues (\"now\", \"revised to\", \"superseded\", \"withdrawn\", later [Mn] overriding earlier).\n2d. UNRESOLVED matters. If two parts of the COMPREHENSION conflict and recency is NOT determinable from its text (including the 2b fallback case, and the case where two prose [Mn] conflict with no ledger entry and no determinable order), treat the matter as UNRESOLVED. Then: a target that presents it as settled in EITHER direction is unfaithful (raise it, citing both [Mn]); a target that presents it as open/disputed, or omits it, is judged normally for that state.\n   (Example — unresolved: [M4] says the deposit was paid, [M7] says it is still outstanding, no later cue or ledger entry orders them; governing state = unresolved. A target asserting \"deposit paid\" OR \"deposit unpaid\" is unfaithful, cite [M4] and [M7]; a target calling it \"disputed\" is judged normally.)\n\n================ SECTION 3 — MATERIAL POINT (one definition, used at every altitude) ================\nA MATERIAL POINT is a live, governing element a reader must not miss: an obligation or action owed (and WHO owes it to WHOM — direction is part of the point), a deadline-in-play, a commercial figure-in-play, a decision/approval/refusal, an unresolved dispute or risk, an unanswered blocking question, or a change of status. Materiality is about CONSEQUENCE, not phrasing: an IMPLIED or cross-message obligation, or one stated softly, is material if a reader's current obligations turn on it — do not dismiss it merely because it is not phrased as an explicit command. Fully-closed-and-immaterial side points and routine pleasantries are NOT material.\n\n================ SECTION 4 — ALTITUDE PER TARGET (the not-lossy bar) ================\nJudge \"lossy\" strictly at each target's OWN altitude, never against a finer one.\n4a. ABSTRACT (paragraph): must carry EVERY material live strand (Section 3, per your 1d list) AND the correct direction/status of each. Omitting ANY material live strand makes it lossy; REVERSING who-owes-whom (e.g., it says WE owe X when the COMPREHENSION shows the COUNTERPARTY owes it), or presenting a strand in the wrong governing state, makes it unfaithful. It may drop fine sub-detail.\n4b. ONE-LINER (one sentence): must LEAD with the most consequential live strand(s) the thread turns on — and must not lead on a non-dominant strand while a dominant live strand exists.\n   - Two strands: if exactly two strands are genuinely co-equal and neither PLAINLY subsumes the other, both must appear; missing one is lossy.\n   - OVERFLOW VALVE (three or more co-equal strands, OR two that cannot both fit a readable sentence): a single sentence cannot carry all. The one-liner is then NOT lossy if it (i) carries the most consequential strand(s) it can fit faithfully and (ii) does not assert the omitted strands are resolved or absent. Surplus co-equal strands are owed to the ABSTRACT, not the sentence — do NOT fail a one-liner that is doing the best a single sentence honestly can. (When you accept a one-liner under this valve, the shed strands must still be checked at abstract altitude under 4a; see 6 hand-off note.)\n   - Fail the one-liner when: NO dominant live strand is present; a required co-equal strand is dropped (two-strand case); it leads on a stale/closed strand while a live one exists; OR it leads on a genuinely minor live strand while a DOMINANT live strand exists and is buried or absent (a misleading-by-emphasis lead, even though the lead itself is true). Also fail it for the same faithfulness defects as any target (fabricated, overstated, wrong direction/status).\n4c. EVENT TAG (terse label): a faithful handle for the thread's dominant matter. GENERIC-BUT-ACCURATE is acceptable and NOT lossy — the floor's atoms supply specificity elsewhere. Fail event_ok ONLY on a concrete SEMANTIC defect you can anchor to [Mn]: (i) UNFAITHFUL — names a topic/status the COMPREHENSION does not make dominant; or (ii) STALE — labels a superseded state as current. (Length is handled separately in Section 6, not here.)\n\n================ SECTION 5 — RECALL-FIRST (the doubt tie-break) ================\n5a. For the ABSTRACT and the ONE-LINER: if after an honest adversarial read you remain in GENUINE doubt whether a material live strand was dropped or a state is stale, resolve toward FAIL and raise the issue — a silent miss is the cardinal failure; a false alarm is cheaply dismissed. A doubt-fail is NOT exempt from the anchor rule: name the specific strand you suspect was dropped/mis-stated and cite the [Mn] that carries it (from your 1d list). If you cannot point to ANY [Mn] carrying a concrete strand, you have no admissible doubt — that is vague unease, not a finding, and the target passes on that point.\n5b. Recall-first operates INSIDE each target's altitude (Section 4); it never promotes a sub-altitude detail into a miss. A truly minor, fully-closed, immaterial point is NOT grounds to fail: if you cannot name in one clause why the point bears on the reader's CURRENT obligations, it is trivia, not a borderline material strand. (Precedence: Section 3's materiality test decides what COUNTS as a strand; recall-first only breaks ties AMONG things that already clear it. 3 filters, 5 breaks ties on the survivors.)\n5c. EVENT TAG is EXEMPT from 5a. For the event tag specifically, 4c's \"generic-but-accurate passes\" WINS over recall-first doubt. Do not fail an event tag merely for being broad, or merely because you are unsure it is specific enough. Fail it only on a concrete WRONG or STALE finding anchored to [Mn] (4c) — i.e., doubt about staleness must rise to a finding you can name and cite, not a vague unease, or the tag passes.\n\n================ SECTION 6 — EVENT TAG LENGTH (mechanical advisory, low trust) ================\nLength is a DETERMINISTIC character count, which is code's job, not yours — and character counting (especially across mixed English/Chinese, where codepoints, bytes, and display width differ) is exactly what an LLM does unreliably. So you do NOT drive event_ok off length. Instead: if the EVENT TAG OBVIOUSLY and grossly overflows a short label (your eyeball read, not a precise count), emit ONE advisory issue tagged \"event:length_advisory\" with the approximate length, and DO NOT flip event_ok on that basis alone. The length_advisory issue is the sole issue type exempt from the 1:1 coupling in Section 8 and from the [Mn]-anchor rule in 1b. event_ok is decided purely on the SEMANTIC tests in 4c/5c.\n\n================ SECTION 7 — EVIDENCE & EMPTY ARTIFACTS ================\n7a. Judge only against the COMPREHENSION text. Import no outside facts.\n7b. EMPTY/BLANK artifact: if any of ABSTRACT, ONE-LINER, or EVENT TAG arrives empty or whitespace-only while the COMPREHENSION contains at least one material live strand, that target is LOSSY -> its flag is false, with type \"empty\" and an issue \"(target): empty — drops all material strands\". Cite the [Mn] of EVERY material live strand it drops (your full 1d list), not one example. (If the COMPREHENSION genuinely has no material content, an empty target is not penalised.)\n\n================ SECTION 8 — VERDICT / ISSUE COUPLING (strict) ================\n8a. Set abstract_ok, summary_ok, event_ok independently — each true=PASS, false=FAIL — using Sections 2-7.\n8b. STRICT 1:1 (semantic issues): every flag set false MUST have >=1 semantic issue naming that target with its [Mn] evidence; every semantic issue MUST flip its target's flag to false. No semantic issue may be \"informational,\" and none may attach to a passing target. The ONLY non-coupled issue is the \"event:length_advisory\" of Section 6, which neither requires nor forbids event_ok=false.\n8c. ONE ISSUE PER DEFECT — no piling on. Raise at most one semantic issue per (target, underlying strand): if a single defective strand could be labelled two ways (e.g., both \"overstated\" and \"wrong_status\", or both \"misattributed\" and \"wrong_direction\"), choose the SINGLE type that most precisely names the defect and cite it once. Multiple issues against one target are admissible only when they concern DIFFERENT strands.\n8d. A prose-vs-ledger reconciliation (Section 2b) is NOT itself an issue and never appears in the issues list. It only sets your grading baseline. Consequently: if reconciling prose against the ledger makes a target CORRECT (the prose looked stale but the governing ledger status vindicates the target), that target simply PASSES with no issue. You raise a status issue ONLY when the target actually contradicts the GOVERNING state you settled on in Section 2.\n8e. Do not invent a defect to look diligent; if a target survives your attack, set its flag true and say nothing about it. passed = (abstract_ok AND summary_ok AND event_ok).\n\n================ SECTION 9 — OUTPUT (JSON only, nothing outside it) ================\n{\n  \"abstract_ok\": <bool>,\n  \"summary_ok\":  <bool>,\n  \"event_ok\":    <bool>,\n  \"passed\":      <bool>,\n  \"issues\": [\n    {\"target\":\"abstract|one-liner|event\",\"type\":\"fabricated|overstated|misattributed|wrong_direction|wrong_status|lossy|empty|length_advisory\",\"evidence\":\"[Mn] (all relevant; or n/a for length_advisory)\",\"detail\":\"one clause: the concrete unfaithful claim or the specific omitted/mis-emphasised material strand\"}\n  ]\n}\nType guide: fabricated = claim with no support; overstated = real point inflated beyond evidence; misattributed = right matter, wrong party/owner; wrong_direction = right obligation and party-set but the arrow is reversed (who-owes-whom flipped); wrong_status = presented in the wrong governing state (stale/closed-as-live or live-as-settled, incl. unresolved-asserted-as-settled per 2d); lossy = a material live strand omitted, or a one-liner that buries/misleads on emphasis (4b); empty = blank target (7b); length_advisory = event overflow (6, non-coupled).\nEmit exactly these keys. \"issues\" is [] when all three flags are true AND no length_advisory applies. Every entry must obey Section 8.\n\nCOMPREHENSION (source of truth, prose + any <<<LEDGER>>>, cites [Mn]):\n{COMPREHENSION}\n\nABSTRACT:\n{ABSTRACT}\n\nONE-LINER:\n{SUMMARY}\n\nEVENT TAG:\n{EVENT}"



def comprehend(subject: str, thread_text: str) -> str:
    return COMPREHEND.replace("{SUBJECT}", subject or "").replace("{THREAD}", thread_text or "")


def refine(subject: str, so_far: str, ledger: str, next_messages: str) -> str:
    return (REFINE.replace("{SUBJECT}", subject or "")
            .replace("{SO_FAR}", so_far or "(none yet)")
            .replace("{LEDGER}", ledger or "[]")
            .replace("{NEXT_MESSAGES}", next_messages or ""))


def distill_facts(comprehension: str, ref_examples: str = "") -> str:
    return (DISTILL_FACTS.replace("{REF_EXAMPLES}", ref_examples or
                                  "RFI, invoice no., case/matter no., ticket/PR no., PO no., clause/section no.")
            .replace("{COMPREHENSION}", comprehension or ""))


def distill_summary(comprehension: str, facet_vocab: str) -> str:
    return (DISTILL_SUMMARY.replace("{FACET_VOCAB}", facet_vocab or "(no facets defined)")
            .replace("{COMPREHENSION}", comprehension or ""))


def actions(comprehension: str, candidate_sheet: str, operator: str = "") -> str:
    head = (f"OPERATOR IDENTITY — the mailbox owner ('our side') is: {operator}. Use it to set is_mine "
            "and direction: an action the operator owes = is_mine true / inbound; one a counterparty "
            "owes = is_mine false / outbound; if the operator is not party to it, internal/unknown.\n\n"
            if operator else "")
    return (head + ACTIONS.replace("{CANDIDATE_SHEET}", candidate_sheet or "[]")
            .replace("{COMPREHENSION}", comprehension or ""))


def qa_semantic(comprehension: str, thread_text: str) -> str:
    return QA_SEMANTIC.replace("{COMPREHENSION}", comprehension or "").replace("{THREAD}", thread_text or "")


def distill_qa(comprehension: str, abstract: str, summary: str, event: str) -> str:
    return (DISTILL_QA.replace("{COMPREHENSION}", comprehension or "")
            .replace("{ABSTRACT}", abstract or "").replace("{SUMMARY}", summary or "")
            .replace("{EVENT}", event or ""))
